(1) Weibull distribution

\[ \begin{aligned} &X\ \sim\ F(x)\ =\ 1-e^{-(\frac{x}{\theta})^\beta}\ \ ,\ \theta > 0\ ,\ \beta>0\ ,\ x>0\\ &\Rightarrow\ F^{-1}(p)\ =\ \theta[-log(1-p)]^{\frac{1}{\beta}}\\ &\text{Let}\ \ U\ \sim\ U(0,1)\ ,\ \text{and}\ \because\ F(X)\ \stackrel{d}{=}\ U\ \sim\ U(0,1)\\ &\therefore\ X\ \stackrel{d}{=}\ F^{-1}(U)\ =\ \theta[-log(1-U)]^{\frac{1}{\beta}}\ \sim\ F\\ \end{aligned} \]

Therefore, we can draw 1000 samples from the U(0,1) distribution, and transform the samples by the inverse cdf to represent the original distribution (namely Weibull distribution).

Take \((\theta\ ,\ \beta)\ =\ (1,5)\) for example. The results are shown as below :

(2) Pareto distribution

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{Target pdf : }\ f_2(x\ ;\ \theta,\beta)\ =\ \frac{\beta}{\theta(1+\frac{x}{\theta})^{\beta+1}}\ ,\ \theta>0\ ,\ \beta>0\ ,\ x>0\\ &\text{Proposal pdf : }\ g_2(x\ ;\ \nu)\ =\ 2\ h(x\ ;\ \nu)\ ,\ x>0\ ,\ \nu>0\ ,\\ &\text{where}\ h(x\ ;\ \nu)\ \text{is the pdf of t distribution with degree of freedom}\ =\ \nu\\ &\text{Compute the value}\ M_2\ \text{, such that}\ M_2\ \geq\ Max_{x>0}\frac{f_2(x\ ;\ \theta,\beta)}{g_2(x\ ;\ \nu)}\\ &\text{Generate}\ Y\ \sim\ g_2\ \text{and}\ U\ \sim\ U(0,1)\ \text{.}\\ &\text{Let}\ X=Y\ \text{if}\ U\ \leq\ \frac{f_2(Y)}{M_2\ g_2(Y)}\ \text{, and reject the draw otherwise.}\\ &\text{Hence, the theoretical efficiency :}\ P(U\ \leq\ \frac{f_2(Y)}{M_2\ g_2(Y)})\ =\ \frac{1}{M_2} \end{aligned} \]

Take \((\theta\ ,\ \beta\ ,\ \nu)\ =\ (15\ ,\ 10\ ,\ 1)\) for example, and find a sufficient large \(M_2\ =\ 1.411\) s.t. the theoretical efficiency \(=\ \frac{1}{M_2}\ \approx\ 70.87\%\). The results are shown as below :

Draw 1000 samples separately from \(g_2\) and \(U(0,1)\), and follow the rejection rule as above to construct our target pdf \(f_2(x)\). The results are shown as below :

Finally, compute the empirical efficiency \(=\ 71.5\%\)

(3) Skewed distribution I

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{Target pdf : }\ f_3(x\ ;\ \gamma)\ =\ \frac{2}{\gamma+\frac{1}{\gamma}}\ \phi(x\gamma^{-sign(x)})\ ,\ x\in R\ ,\ \gamma\ >\ 0\\ &\text{Proposal pdf : }\ g_3(x\ ;\ \mu,\sigma^2)\ \sim\ N(\mu\ ,\ \sigma^2)\ \ ,\ x\ \in\ R\ ,\ \mu\in R\ ,\ \sigma^2>0\\ &\text{Compute the value}\ M_3\ \text{, such that}\ M_3\ \geq\ Max_{x\in R}\frac{f_3(x\ ;\ \gamma)}{g_3(x\ ;\ \mu,\sigma^2)}\\ &\text{Generate}\ Y\ \sim\ g_3\ \text{and}\ U\ \sim\ U(0,1)\ \text{.}\\ &\text{Let}\ X=Y\ \text{if}\ U\ \leq\ \frac{f_3(Y)}{M_3\ g_3(Y)}\ \text{, and reject the draw otherwise.}\\ &\text{Hence, the theoretical efficiency :}\ P(U\ \leq\ \frac{f_3(Y)}{M_3\ g_3(Y)})\ =\ \frac{1}{M_3} \end{aligned} \]

Take \((\gamma\ ,\ \mu\ ,\ \sigma^2)\ =\ (1.5\ ,\ 0.3\ ,\ 1.5)\) for example, and find a sufficient large \(M_3\ =\ 1.42\) s.t. the theoretical efficiency \(=\ \frac{1}{M_3}\ \approx\ 70.42\%\). The results are shown as below :

Draw 1000 samples separately from \(g_3\) and \(U(0,1)\), and follow the rejection rule as above to construct our target pdf \(f_3(x)\). The results are shown as below :

Finally, compute the empirical efficiency \(=\ 70.3\%\)

(a)

\[ \begin{aligned} &\text{Target pdf : }\ f_{4.1}(x\ ;\ \alpha,\nu_1)\ =\ 2h(x\ ;\ \nu_1)\ G(\alpha x\ ;\ \nu_1)\ ,\ x\in R\ ,\ \alpha\in R\ ,\ \nu_1>0\\ &\text{where}\ h(x)\ \text{and}\ G(x)\ \text{are the pdf and cdf of t distribution with}\ \nu_1\ \text{degree of freedom}\\ &\text{Proposal pdf : }\ g_{4.1}(x\ ;\ \nu_2)\ \sim\ t(\nu_2)\ \ ,\ x\ \in\ R\ ,\ \nu_2>0\\ &\text{Compute the value}\ M_{4.1}\ \text{, such that}\ M_{4.1}\ \geq\ Max_{x\in R}\frac{f_{4.1}(x\ ;\ \alpha,\nu_1)}{g_{4.1}(x\ ;\ \nu_2)}\\ &\text{Generate}\ Y\ \sim\ g_{4.1}\ \text{and}\ U\ \sim\ U(0,1)\ \text{.}\\ &\text{Let}\ X=Y\ \text{if}\ U\ \leq\ \frac{f_{4.1}(Y)}{M_{4.1}\ g_{4.1}(Y)}\ \text{, and reject the draw otherwise.}\\ &\text{Hence, the theoretical efficiency :}\ P(U\ \leq\ \frac{f_{4.1}(Y)}{M_{4.1}\ g_{4.1}(Y)})\ =\ \frac{1}{M_{4.1}} \end{aligned} \]

Take \((\alpha\ ,\ \nu_1\ ,\ \nu_2)\ =\ (1\ ,\ 2\ ,\ 1)\) for example, and find a sufficient large \(M_{4.1}\ =\ 2.015\) s.t. the theoretical efficiency \(=\ \frac{1}{M_{4.1}}\ \approx\ 49.63\%\). The results are shown as below :

Now I decided to construct the skewed-double-exponential distribution, then \(G(x)\) and \(h(x)\) are the cdf and pdf of double-exponential distribution. Later, I will use both methods in Problems (3) and (4).

\[ \begin{aligned} &\textbf{Method 1.}\\ &h(x\ ;\ \lambda)\ =\ \frac{1}{2}\lambda e^{-\lambda|x|}\ ,\ x\in R\ ,\ \lambda>0\\ &G(x\ ;\ \lambda)\ =\ \int_{-\infty}^x h(u\ ;\ \lambda)\ du\ =\ \frac{1}{2}[1+sign(x)(1-e^{-\lambda|x|})]\ ,\ x\in R\ ,\ \lambda>0\\ &\text{By method in Problem (3), define}\\ &\text{Target pdf :}\ f_{4.2.1}(x\ ;\ \lambda,\gamma)\ =\ \frac{2}{\gamma+\frac{1}{\gamma}}\ h(x\gamma^{-sign(x)}\ ;\ \lambda)\ ,\ x\in R\ ,\ \lambda>0\ ,\ \gamma>0\\ &\text{Proposal pdf : }\ g_{4.2.1}(x\ ;\ \nu)\ \sim\ t(\nu)\ \ ,\ x\ \in\ R\ ,\ \nu>0\\ &\text{Compute the value}\ M_{4.2.1}\ \text{, such that}\ M_{4.2.1}\ \geq\ Max_{x\in R}\frac{f_{4.2.1}(x\ ;\ \lambda,\gamma)}{g_{4.2.1}(x\ ;\ \nu)}\\ &\text{Generate}\ Y\ \sim\ g_{4.2.1}\ \text{and}\ U\ \sim\ U(0,1)\ \text{.}\\ &\text{Let}\ X=Y\ \text{if}\ U\ \leq\ \frac{f_{4.2.1}(Y)}{M_{4.2.1}\ g_{4.2.1}(Y)}\ \text{, and reject the draw otherwise.}\\ &\text{Hence, the theoretical efficiency :}\ P(U\ \leq\ \frac{f_{4.2.1}(Y)}{M_{4.2.1}\ g_{4.2.1}(Y)})\ =\ \frac{1}{M_{4.2.1}} \end{aligned} \]

(5) 2-dimension distribution

The target pdf : \[ f(x,y)\ =\ 2(1-x)(1-y)(1-xy)^{-3}\ ,\ 0<x<1\ ,\ 0<y<1 \]

我們可以發現 f(x,y) 有以下特徵：
1. 圖形對稱於 y=x
2. (x,y) 皆偏小和皆偏大處 pdf 數值較高，特別是偏大處(即圖形右上角)

Let \[ \left\{ \begin{aligned} u\ =\ log\frac{x}{1-x}\\ v\ =\ log\frac{y}{1-y} \end{aligned} \right.\ \Rightarrow\ \left\{ \begin{aligned} x\ =\ \frac{e^u}{1+e^u}\\ y\ =\ \frac{e^v}{1+e^v} \end{aligned} \right. \] And then transform the target pdf into \[ g(u,v)\ =\ f(\frac{e^u}{1+e^u}\ ,\ \frac{e^v}{1+e^v})|J|\ =\ \frac{2e^ue^v}{(1+e^u+e^v)^3}\ ,\ u\in R\ ,\ v\in R \] Compute the marginal pdf, marginal cdf and joint cdf of g(u,v) \[ \left\{ \begin{aligned} &g_1(u)\ =\ e^u(1+e^u)^{-2}\ \ and\ \ G_1(u)\ =\ 1-(1+e^u)^{-1}\ ,\ u\in R\\ &g_2(v)\ =\ e^v(1+e^v)^{-2}\ \ and\ \ G_2(v)\ =\ 1-(1+e^v)^{-1}\ ,\ v\in R\\ &G(u,v)\ =\ (1+e^u+e^v)^{-1}\ \ ,\ \ u\in R\ ,\ v\in R \end{aligned} \right. \] \[ \Rightarrow\ \left\{ \begin{aligned} G_1(U)\ \overset{d}{=}\ A\ \sim\ U(0,1)\\ G_2(V)\ \overset{d}{=}\ B\ \sim\ U(0,1) \end{aligned} \right. \] By Sklar’s Theorem : \[ \begin{aligned} G(u,v)\ &=\ P(U\leq u\ ,\ V\leq v)\ =\ P(G_1(U)\leq G_1(u)\ ,\ G_2(V)\leq G_2(v))\ =\ P(G_1(U)\leq a\ ,\ G_2(V)\leq b)\\ &=\ C(a\ ,\ b)\ =\ (1+\frac{a}{1-a}+\frac{b}{1-b})^{-1}\ ,\ 0<a<1\ ,\ 0<b<1 \end{aligned} \] And \[ c(a\ ,\ b)\ =\ \frac{\partial^2C}{\partial a\partial b}\ =\ 2(1-a)(1-b)(1-ab)^{-3}\ (\text{The same form as }f(x,y)) \] which is the joint pdf of a and b, where \(A\ \sim\ U(0,1)\) and \(B|A=a^*\ \sim\ f_{B|A=a^*}(b)\ =\ 2(1-a^*)(1-b)(1-a^*b)^{-3\ ,\ 0<b<1}\)

進行以下步驟即可抽出 c(a,b) (即f(x,y))的 empirical pdf
1. 抽取 10000 個樣本 \(a_i\ \sim\ U(0,1)\ ,\ i\ =\ 1,2,...,10000\)
2. 對每個 \(a_i\) 建構 conditional distribution \(f_{B|A=a_i}\)視為 target distribuion，並以U(0,1)為 proposal distribution 進行 rejection sampling (一個\(a_i\)僅抽出一個相對應的\(b_i\))
3. \((a_i,b_i)\ ,\ i=1,2,...,10000\) 即為從 c(a,b)(f(x,y))所抽出的樣本

(x,y) 的散佈圖看起來右上及左下資料點較為集中，以下繪製二維的 density plot 較為容易觀察

可以觀察到抽出的樣本在二維空間的分布和 target pdf 有許多特徵相似：右上和左下數據較為集中且以右上最多，圖形對稱於y=x

x 和 y 的 marginal empirical pdf 和 U(0,1) 相當接近，也符合 f(x,y) 是一個 copula pdf 的特性。

Theoretical average efficiency : \[\frac{1}{10000}\sum_{i=1}^{10000}\frac{1}{M_i}\ \approx\ 62.97\%\]
